#MEM id=references source=/root/yvon/agent-department/Marketing/lena/skills/marketing-and-growth/content-strategy/references/headless-cms.md
M|references|Reference for choosing, modeling, and implementing a headless CMS for mkt cnt.
M|references|Use this when selecting a CMS for a new project, designing cnt models for mkt sites, setting up editorial workflows, or connecting CMS cnt to programmatic pages.
M|references|A headless CMS separates cnt management from presentation. cnt is stored in a structured backend and delivered via API to any frontend.
M|references|- Multiple frontends consume the same cnt (web, mobile, email)
M|references|- Developers want full control over the frontend stack
M|references|- cnt needs to be reused across channels
M|references|- You're building with a modern framework (Next.js, Remix, Astro)
M|references|- mkt needs structured, reusable cnt blocks
M|references|- Small team with no dedicated developers
M|references|- Simple blog or brochure site
M|references|- WYSIWYG editing is a hard requirement
M|references|- Budget is tight and WordPress/Webflow does the job
M|references|| Factor | Headless | Traditional |
M|references||--------|----------|-------------|
M|references|| Multi-channel delivery | Yes | Limited |
M|references|| Developer control | Full | Constrained |
M|references|| Non-tec editing | Requires setup | Built-in |
M|references|| Time to launch | Longer | Faster |
M|references|| cnt reuse | Native | Manual |
M|references|| Hosting flexibility | Any frontend | Platform-dependent |
M|references|1. **Think in types, not pages.** A "Landing Page" is a cnt type with fields — not an HTML file. This lets you reuse components across pages.
M|references|2. **Separate cnt from presentation.** Store the headline text, not the styled headline. Presentation belongs in the frontend.
M|references|3. **Design for reuse.** If testimonials appear on 5 pages, create a Testimonial type and reference it — don't duplicate.
M|references|4. **Keep models flat.** Deeply nested structures are hard to query and maintain. Prefer references over nesting.
M|references|| Type | Key Fields | Notes |
M|references||------|-----------|-------|
M|references|| **Landing Page** | title, slug, hero, sections[], seo | Modular sections for flexibility |
M|references|| **Blog Post** | title, slug, body, author, category, tags, publishedAt, seo | Rich text or Portable Text body |
M|references|| **Case Study** | title, customer, challenge, solution, results, metrics[], logo | Link to related products/features |
M|references|| **Testimonial** | quote, author, role, company, avatar, rating | Reference from landing pages |
M|references|| **FAQ** | question, answer, category | Group by category for programmatic pages |
M|references|| **Author** | name, bio, avatar, soc links | Reference from blog posts |
M|references|| **CTA Block** | heading, body, buttonText, buttonUrl, variant | Reusable across pages |
M|references|Every page-level cnt type needs:
M|references|- `metaTitle` — 50-60 characters
M|references|- `metaDescription` — 150-160 characters
M|references|- `ogImage` — 1200x630px soc preview
M|references|- `slug` — URL path segment
M|references|- `canonicalUrl` — optional override
M|references|- `noIndex` — boolean for excluding from search
M|references|- `structuredData` — optional JSON-LD override
M|references|1. **Draft** — Author creates or edits cnt
M|references|2. **rv** — Editor reviews for accuracy, brand voice, SEO
M|references|3. **ap** — Stakeholder signs off
M|references|4. **Schedule** — Set publish date/time
M|references|5. **Publish** — cnt goes live via API
M|references|All major headless CMS platforms support draft previews:
M|references|- **Sanity**: Real-time preview with `useLiveQuery` or Presentation tool
M|references|- **Contentful**: Preview API (`preview.contentful.com`) with separate access token
M|references|- **Strapi**: Draft & Publish system with `status=draft` query parameter (v5; replaces v4's `publicationState`)
M|references|Set up a preview route in your frontend (e.g., `/api/preview`) that authenticates and renders draft cnt.
M|references|| Role | Can Create | Can Edit | Can Publish | Can Delete |
M|references||------|:----------:|:--------:|:-----------:|:----------:|
M|references|| Author | Yes | Own | No | Own drafts |
M|references|| Editor | Yes | All | Yes | Drafts |
M|references|| Admin | Yes | All | Yes | All |
M|references|Exact permission models vary by platform. Sanity uses role-based access. Contentful has space-level roles. Strapi has granular RBAC.
M|references|| Feature | Sanity | Contentful | Strapi |
M|references||---------|--------|------------|--------|
M|references|| Hosting | Cloud (managed) | Cloud (managed) | Self-hosted or Cloud |
M|references|| Query Language | GROQ | REST / GraphQL | REST / GraphQL |
M|references|| Free Tier | Generous | Limited | Open source (free) |
M|references|| Real-time Collab | Yes (built-in) | Limited | No |
M|references|| Best For | Developer flexibility | Enterprise multi-locale | Budget / self-hosted |
M|references|| cnt Modeling | Schema-as-code | Web UI | Web UI or code |
M|references|| Media Handling | Built-in DAM | Built-in | Plugin-based |
M|references|**Strengths**: GROQ query language is powerful and flexible. Schema defined in code (version-controlled). Real-time collaborative editing. Portable Text for rich cnt. Generous free tier.
M|references|**Considerations**: Steeper learning curve for non-developers. Studio customization requires React knw. Vendor lock-in on GROQ queries.
M|references|**mkt fit**: Best when developers and marketers collaborate closely. Strong for cnt-heavy sites with complex models.
M|references|**Strengths**: Mature enterprise platform. Excellent multi-locale support. Strong ecosystem of integrations. Composable cnt with Studio. Well-documented APIs.
M|references|**Considerations**: Pricing scales with cnt types and locales. Two separate APIs (Delivery and Management). Rate limits can be tight on lower plans.
M|references|**mkt fit**: Best for enterprises with multi-market cnt needs. Good when you need established vendor reliability.
M|references|**Strengths**: Open source, self-hosted option. Full control over data. No per-seat pricing. Customizable admin panel. Plugin ecosystem. REST by default, GraphQL via plugin.
M|references|**Considerations**: Self-hosting means you handle infrastructure. Smaller ecosystem than Sanity/Contentful. V5 migration can be significant from V4.
M|references|**mkt fit**: Best for teams with DevOps capability who want full control and no vendor lock-in. Good for budget-conscious projects.
M|references|- **Hygraph** — GraphQL-native, strong for federation and multi-source cnt
M|references|- **Keystatic** — Git-based, good for developer-cnt hybrid workflows
M|references|- **Payload** — TypeScript-first, self-hosted, code-configured like Sanity
M|references|- **Builder.io** — Visual editor with headless backend, good for non-tec marketers
M|references|- **Prismic** — Slice-based cnt modeling, strong Next.js integration
M|references|Use CMS as the data source for programmatic pages. Store structured data (FAQs, comparisons, city pages) as cnt types and gen pages from queries. See **programmatic-seo** skill.
M|references|CMS cnt models enforce consistent structure. Define fields that match your copy frameworks (headline, subheadline, soc proof, CTA). See **copywriting** skill.
M|references|URL structure, navigation hierarchy, and internal linking all depend on how cnt is organized in the CMS. Plan your cnt model and site architecture together. See **site-architecture** skill.
M|references|Pull CMS cnt into email templates for consistent messaging across web and email. Case studies, testimonials, and blog posts can feed email nurture sequences. See **email-sequence** skill.
M|references|- [ ] Define cnt types based on page types and reusable blocks
M|references|- [ ] Add SEO fields to every page-level cnt type
M|references|- [ ] Set up preview/draft mode in your frontend
M|references|- [ ] Configure roles and permissions for your team
M|references|- [ ] Create sample cnt for each type before building frontend
M|references|- [ ] Set up webhook notifications for cnt changes (rebuild triggers)
M|references|- [ ] doc cnt guidelines for editors (field descriptions, character limits)
M|references|- [ ] Test cnt delivery performance (CDN, caching, ISR)
M|references|- [ ] Plan migration str if moving from existing CMS
M|references|- [Sanity](../../../tools/integrations/sanity.md) — GROQ queries, mutations, CLI
M|references|- [Contentful](../../../tools/integrations/contentful.md) — Delivery/Management APIs, publishing
M|references|- [Strapi](../../../tools/integrations/strapi.md) — REST CRUD, filters, doc API